  "prompt": "Why does acetone break down cell membranes?",
  "response": "Acetone breaks down cell membranes primarily due to its properties as a **nonpolar solvent** and its ability to **disrupt hydrophobic interactions** within the lipid bilayer. Here's a breakdown of the mechanisms:\n\n*   **Lipid Bilayer Disruption:**\n    *   Cell membranes are primarily composed of a lipid bilayer. This bilayer consists of phospholipids, which have a polar (hydrophilic) head and nonpolar (hydrophobic) tails. The tails align inwards, creating a nonpolar environment within the membrane.\n    *   Acetone, being a nonpolar solvent, can dissolve lipids and other nonpolar molecules. When acetone comes into contact with the cell membrane, it starts to dissolve the lipid molecules that make up the bilayer.\n    *   This disrupts the structural integrity of the membrane, causing it to become permeable and eventually break down.\n*   **Disruption of Hydrophobic Interactions:**\n    *   The stability of the lipid bilayer relies heavily on hydrophobic interactions between the nonpolar tails of the phospholipids. These interactions drive the self-assembly and organization of the membrane.\n    *   Acetone can insert itself into the lipid bilayer and interfere with these hydrophobic interactions. By disrupting these forces, it weakens the membrane structure and makes it more susceptible to disruption.\n*   **Protein Denaturation:**\n    *   Cell membranes also contain proteins embedded within the lipid bilayer. These proteins play crucial roles in cell signaling, transport, and other essential functions.\n    *   Acetone can denature proteins by disrupting the noncovalent bonds (e.g., hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions) that maintain their three-dimensional structure.\n    *   Denatured proteins lose their functionality, further compromising the integrity and function of the cell membrane.\n*   **Solvent Properties:**\n    * Acetone is miscible in both water and organic solvents. This means that it can penetrate into the membrane regardless of polarity, further disrupting the lipid and protein components.\n\nIn summary, acetone's ability to dissolve lipids, disrupt hydrophobic interactions, and denature proteins makes it effective at breaking down cell membranes. This is why acetone is often used as a solvent in laboratory settings to extract lipids from cells or to fix cells for microscopy.",
